3 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY Section 2, Chapter 372, O.S.L.
4 2023 (27A O.S. Supp. 2024, Section 3-8-102), is amended to read as
5 follows:
6 Section 3-8-102. A. As used in the Terry Peach North Canadian
7 Watershed Water Restoration Act:
8 1. "Commission" means the Oklahoma Conservation Commission;
9 2. "Harmful woody species" means a tree or shrub species that
10 is rapidly encroaching into adjoining lands and is likely to cause
11 harm to the environment or economy. Harmful woody species include,
12 but are not limited to, Juniperus virginiana (Eastern Redcedar),
13 Juniperus scopulorum (Rocky Mountain juniper), Juniperus monosperma
14 (oneseed juniper) and, Tamarix ramosissima (salt cedar), Juniperus
15 pinchotii (Redberry juniper), Juniper ashei (ashe juniper), and
16 Prosopis glandulosa (honey mesquite); and
17 3. "North Canadian Watershed" means the an area of land in
18 Oklahoma that drains or sheds water into the North Canadian River a
19 waterway or water basin.
20 B. There is hereby created a pilot statewide program to remove
21 or eradicate harmful woody species in the North Canadian Watershed
22 watersheds to be administered by the Oklahoma Conservation
23 Commission. To accomplish the goals listed in this section, the
24 Commission is authorized to use the funds available in the North
HB2162 HFLR Page 2
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 Cana dian Watershed Water Restoration Revolving Fund established in
2 Section 3 of this act Section 3-8-103 of this title. The purpose of
3 the program is to manage and eradicate, where possible, harmful
4 woody species that damage grazing lands, create significant wildfire
5 risk, reduce wildlife habitat and reduce water flow into the North
6 Canadian River waterways and water basins.
7 C. In administering the pilot program, the Commission shall:
8 1. Cooperate with landowners, state agencies, and other
9 political subdivisions for removal of harmful woody species;
10 2. Measure the density of harmful woody species and estimate
11 water used by those species;
12 3. Create a study using a parallel watershed with no control of
13 harmful woody species;
14 4. Utilize available funds to cost-share with landowners for
15 expenses incurred in the eradication of harmful woody species by
16 prescribed burn, biological controls, mechanical removal, or
17 herbicide applications;
18 5. Develop grant programs with conservation districts, rural
19 fire departments, and prescribe burn associations for resources
20 needed for prescribed burns, mechanical removal, biological control,
21 or herbicide applications on harmful woody species;
22 6. Bring attention to the problems posed by harmful woody
23 species to create awareness, demonstrate value to all stakeholders,
24 and encourage landowners to participate in the program; and
